In a woman with chronic hypertension, new-onset proteinuria (Option A), thrombocytopenia (<75,000 platelets, Option B), or significant increases in blood pressure (Option C) are established indicators of superimposed preeclampsia. However, fresh retinal hyperemic changes (Option D) are typically associated with long-standing hypertension rather than being a sign of newly developed preeclampsia. Retinal findings like exudates or hemorrhages usually reflect chronic vascular stress and do not signify active superimposition of preeclampsia. Therefore, option D does not meet criteria for superimposed preeclampsia.

